UV spectroscopy¶

This tutorial proposes a way to treat a series a data within several files. In this example, photon activation tandem mass spectra have been measured for different precursor ions. Each file corresponds to a particular wavelenght (photon energy).

We need to get the ion abundance for the ion of interest in each file.

In [1]:
using msJ

The mzXML files are storred in the data folder. We set the current directory to this folder.

In [2]:
cd("~/data/")

The readdir() function lists the files and directories and returns a vector containing the name of the files inside the directory.

We can look into the files using the msJ.info function

In [5]:
info(files[1])
Out[5]:
5-element Array{String,1}:
 "502 scans"       
 "MS2- 929  CID"   
 "MS2- 1084  CID"  
 "MS2- 1301  CID"  
 "MS2- 1626.5  CID"

We lear from the output of the info function that:

  • all the mass spectra are MS/MS spectra (MS2)
  • all the mass have been measured in the negative ion mode (MS2-)
  • we have 4 precursor ion corresponding to different charge states of BPTI:
    • m/z 929
    • m/z 1084
    • m/z 1301
    • m/z 1626

The protein BPTI has a mass of ~ 6500 Da. Therefore the different precursor ion masses correspond to the following chage states:

  • m/z 929 - $[M-7H]^{7-}$
  • m/z 1084 - $[M-6H]^{6-}$
  • m/z 1301 - $[M-5H]^{5-}$
  • m/z 1626 - $[M-4H]^{4-}$

Each of these precursor ions has been photon activated in the photon energy ranging from 4.5 to 7eV with 0.2 eV steps.

We will restrict ourselves to the $[M-7H]^{7-}$ charge state.

First, lets create a variable energy to hold the different photon energy and another one called wavelength for the wavelengths.

In [6]:
energy = zeros(16)                  # energy has 16 points, corresponding to the 16 values of the `files` vector (above).
energy = [4.5 + i*0.2 for i=1:16]

Now, for each file, we have to:

  • get average mass spectra for the m/z 929 precursor using the average function
  • then we need to measure the ion abundance for the precursor (m/z 928.83) and the product ions (m/z 1083.75, 1076.2, 1300.41 and 1291.83)
  • the variance, which is stored the field s, will be used to calculate the error bars of our measurements. We will use the variance s to calculate the standard error of the mean, given by SEM = s / N, where N is the sample size.

We will use two Julia packages to do this: the DataFrames and Measurements packages. DataFrames is a very useful to manage data and Measurements is used to get the error propagation.

See the documentation of the packages:

  • DataFrames.jl
  • Measurements.jl
In [11]:
using DataFrames
using Measurements

We will also use a convenient function of the msJpackage: the num2pnt function. It returns the index of a vector for which the vector value is closest to the input valule: num2pnt(vector, value).

In [13]:
# Below we declare the DataFrame variable to store our data:
m7 = DataFrame(P = zeros(0),    # vector to store the precursor ion abundance
               PD1 = zeros(0),  # vector to store the abundance of the loss of 1 electron
               PD2 = zeros(0),  # vector to store the abundance of the loss of 2 electrons
               Abs = zeros(0),  # vector to store the UV spectrum
               Abs = zeros(0)) # vector to store the error bars of the UV spectrum

for file in files  # loop over all the mzXML files of interest
    println(file)  # get the name of the file on which we are working
    s = load(file); # loading the file in the variable s

    a = average(s, msJ.Precursor(929)) # get the average mass spectrum for precursor at m/z 929
    i = num2pnt(a.mz, 928.83)   # get the indice corresponding to the maximum
    maxi = maximum(a.int[i-10:i+10]) # get the maximum of the ms peak in the vicinity of i
    maxi = a.s[num2pnt(a.int,maxi)] # get the variance (a.s) for that ms peak
    maxi = maxi / sqrt(length(a.num)) # get the standard error of the mean
    P = maxi  maxi     # associate the error with the value (Measurement object)
    
# Repeat the above procedure for the first electron detachment
    i = num2pnt(a.mz, 1083.75)
    maxi = maximum(a.int[i-10:i+10])
    maxi = (a.s[num2pnt(a.int,maxi)] / sqrt(length(a.num)))
    PD1 = maxi  maxi 

# Repeat the above procedure for the fragment @ m/z 1076.2
    i = num2pnt(a.mz, 1076.2)
    maxi = maximum(a.int[i-10:i+10])
    maxi = (a.s[num2pnt(a.int,maxi)] / sqrt(length(a.num)))
    PD2 = maxi  maxi 

# Repeat again for the second electron detachment
    i = num2pnt(a.mz, 1300.41)
    maxi = maximum(a.int[i-10:i+10])
    maxi = (a.s[num2pnt(a.int,maximum(a.int[i-10:i+10]))] / sqrt(length(a.num)))
    PD3 = maxi  maxi

# Repeat again for the fragment @ m/z 1291.83
    i = num2pnt(a.mz, 1291.83)
    maxi = maximum(a.int[i-10:i+10])
    maxi = (a.s[num2pnt(a.int,maximum(a.int[i-10:i+10]))] / sqrt(length(a.num)))
    PD4 = maxi  maxi

    TIC = P + PD1 + PD2 + PD3 + PD4   # Calculate the total ion abundance

# We will now store in the m7 DataFrame the different value computed at each photon energy
    push!(m7,                 # We will insert into the m7 dataframe
        [P.val,               # The value of precursor ion abundance
        (PD1 + PD2/TIC).val,        # The normalized abundance for the product of the photodetachment
        (PD3 + PD4/TIC).val,        # The normalized abundance for the prodcut of 2 electron detachment
        log(TIC / P).val,     # We calculate here the pseudo Absorbance and storre the value
        log(TIC / P).err] )   # We storre here the error of the absorbance.
end

p1 = plot(energy, m7.P, label = "Precursor", legend=:bottomright)

plot!(p2, energy, m7.PD2, label ="")
p3 = plot(energy, m7.Abs, label = "Absorbance", legend=:bottomright)

plot(p1, p2, p3,
    layout = (1,3), size = (600,200),
)
Out[14]:

Now, we need to take into account the photon flux over the spectral range.

To read the flux from a file, we will use the Delimited package:

In [15]:
using DelimitedFiles
In [16]:
flux = readdlm("~/data/photon-flux.txt", skipstart = 2, Float64)
flux[:,2] /= maximum(flux[:,2]);   # We just need a relative flux, so can normalise it to its maximum.

The Photon flux has been measured at different photon energy value than those used here for the photon activation of BPTI. Therefore, we need to interpolate the flux to our energy scale. This is achieved using the Interpolations paclage.

In [17]:
using Interpolations
In [18]:
extrap = LinearInterpolation(flux[:,1],                      # energy scale of the flux
                             flux[:,2],                      # corresponding flux
                             extrapolation_bc = Line())      # ne want to be able to extrapolate if necessary
flux_int = [extrap(x) for x in energy ]                      # We use the `extrap` function to get flux values
                                                             # at the present photon energy values.

Lets plot the photon flux and the interpolated values to check.

In [19]:
gr()
p1 = plot(flux[:,1], flux[:,2],
    xlims = (4.5, 8),
    label = "Relative Photon flux", 
    legend = :topleft,
    xaxis = "Photon energy (eV)",
    yaxis = "Relative photon flux (a.u.)",
    size = (400,300)
)
scatter!(p1, energy, flux_int, label = "Interpolated value")
Out[19]:

We see from the above figure that the interpolation went fine, but we have a point which has been extrpolated at 7.5 eV.

Now, we will plot the absorbance results normalized to the photon flux. Note that the last point of the scan is not correct because it was measured with no photon flux.

In [20]:
m7_spectrum  = (m7.Abs . m7.Abs) ./ flux_int ;
